{"key":"processedPost-8515187","value":{"id":8515187,"first":8511082,"last":8518611,"when":1213296145,"utime":"06/12/08 09:42 PM","content":"First, dump the blue tub.&nbsp; Mushrooms prefer light in the 'blue' color temperature range, and a blue tub reflects that color light back at you, effectively filtering it from your mushrooms that need it.<br /><br />Second, air exchange is one of the most important pinning triggers.&nbsp; Rather than being concerned that the crack in your tub will 'let air out' you need to be devising ways to let lots of fresh air IN to the tubs.<br /><br />Third, Moisture on the sides of the tub indicate a temperature differential between the tub and the outside air.&nbsp; Condensation forms on the warm side.&nbsp; That's why the inside of your windows get condensation in the winter, even though the air in your house is dry.&nbsp; Condensation has <i>nothing</i> to do with humidity.&nbsp; In fact, it 'steals' humidity from the air in your tub to form on the sides.<br /><br />Fourth, you're supposed to inoculate around the edges of the cake, right against the glass so the inoculant runs down the glass to coat more of the cake.&nbsp; Inoculate in four places to ensure even, full colonization.&nbsp; However, given enough time, your method will colonize, so this is not your major problem.<br /><br />Fix the first three problems above and watch your cakes explode.<br />RR","title":"Re: 1 out of 6 cakes fruiting. WTF?","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}